nity of Mount Isa, Queensland, Australia, and the mill town of Corner Brook, Newfoundland, Canada. White pinpoints crucial differences between the towns' experiences by contrasting each region's histories from various perspectives—business, urban, labour, civic, and socio-cultural. Company Towns also makes use of a sizable collection of previously neglected oral history sources and town records, providing an illuminating portrait of divergence that defies efforts to impose structure on the company town phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunity lifevCase studies. 0aCompany townsvCase studies. 0aCorporationsxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aResource-based communitiesvCase studies. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269576440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442695764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442695764.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK